    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p>Previously misidentified as <i>Limaria rotundata </i>(which remains a valid species). Previous name <i>Ostrea tuberculata.</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_925",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Shell valves equal, delicate translucent white and ornamented with fine radiating ridges. A small lateral ‘ear’ next to the straight hinge. Live animal bright red and edged with numerous long, conspicuous, mobile tentacles. Foot has a bright purple tip.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_926",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Reaches 42 mm shell height.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_927",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Mediterranean, West Africa, southwards to Angola and South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Saldanha Bay to Eastern Cape.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_928",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>A striking species that lives singly and unattached under boulders, in rock crevices or kelp holdfasts or similarly sheltered habitats, such as between tunicates or other sedentary organisms. At first sight the elongated tentacles could be confused with those of a sea anemone. Can swim clumsily by clapping the shell valves together, much like a scallop. The brightly-coloured marginal tentacles aid in defence by secreting acrid, sticky mucus and can be shed at will. Loose tentacles wriggle like discarded lizard tails, and this distracts predators. New tentacles develop rapidly to replace lost ones.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_929",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>All bivalves feed by drawing water in then filtering it thought the enlarged sieve-like gills. Food particles filtered from the water are transported by cilia to the edge of the gill and then to the mouth.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_930",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Details unknown, but almost all bivalves are broadcast spawners.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_931",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Several similar species occur in the more tropical waters of KwaZulu-Natal, but this is the only common coastal species in the Western Cape although <i>L. loscombii </i>also occurs in deeper offshore waters on the Agulhas Bank.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_932",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa. (Fourth edition) Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 150).<br><br>Kilburn, RN (1998). The Limidae of South Africa and Mozambique (Mollusca: Bivalvia): genera <i>Limaria, <i>Limatula</i>, <i>Divarilima</i>, <i>Ctenoides</i> and <i>Fukama</i>. <i>Annals of the Natal Museum</i>, 39, 203-247.<br><br>Kilburn, R & Rippey, E (1982). Sea Shells of Southern Africa. Macmillan South Africa, Johannesburg (p. 169, as <i>L. rotundata</i>).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_933",
            "longText": null,
